check the following example to understand the required feature.

```
return (tree, context) => {
  //we want to immediately apply this template to the current tree, so the tree itself contains the files that generated via templates, and tree.exists('files form templates') == true
   apply(url(`./files`), [template({})]);

 console.log(tree.exists('./templateFile.txt')) //this should outputs true;  `templateFile.txt` created by applying template into the current tree

 tree.create('anotherFile.txt','---')
 return tree; // now tree contains `templateFile.txt`

}
```
this can be useful if you want to use external functions (not included in collection.json) that return rules, and you want to apply these rules to your tree before dealing with it.

these functions are not included in collection.json, so we cannot use` externalSchematic()` nor `schematic()`

chaining the rules is not useful, because you may want to check some files from the previous applied rules before applying new rules.

# üêû Bug report

### Description

Moving files as part of a schematic can cause an error to be thrown:

```bash
  Message:
    Error: This should never happen. Path: "/projects/bar".
```

It seems to happen if those files were created by a previous rule and the move is done by copy and deletion.

(As an aside here, it _seems_ that delete operations are hoisted somehow...whenever they occur in a schematic, the logger output shows them to always happen first, this is *not* what I'd expect)

I'm aware that there is a `move` rule in `@angular-devkit/schematics/src/rules`, but this **does not work**. Attempting to use this rule to move files from one folder to another results in this error: `ENOENT: no such file or directory, rename '<source>' -> '<destination>'`

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

```ts
export function move(schema: Schema): Rule {
  return (host: Tree, _context: SchematicContext): Tree => {
    const dir = host.getDir(schema.source);
    dir.visit(file => {
      const newPath = file.replace(schema.source, schema.destination);

      const buffer = host.read(file);
      if (buffer === null) {
        return;
      }

      host.create(newPath, buffer);
    });

    host.delete(schema.source);

    return host;
  };
}
```

See also: https://github.com/jdpearce/move-schematic

NB - this schematic will probably work if run against a pre-existing workspace, but when the tree is set up by another schematic, as in the spec file, that's when the error is thrown.

